Catalytic Agent

In the traditional, chemical sense of the concept, a catalytic agent is an element/entity/idea/thing that brings two other, unrelated elements together and allows them to act in a new way without changing its own nature.

This phrase was first coined in 1976 by Amie Hill, to describe her understanding of my primary function. She had business cards made for me and it has been part of my identity ever since.

